TSRs

    A number of issues in the design of Terminate-and-Stay-Resident
    programs (TSRs) need to be handled differently in protected mode than
    in real mode.  The total process is complicated enough so that we have
    created a number of special functions to make developing protected-mode
    TSRs easier.  All of these are included in the standard DOS/4G API
    libraries.  These functions are designed to deal with the issues of
    protected-mode TSR development described for this example.
    
    Critical issues for TSRs that require the use of the helper fuctions
    include:

    Installation: Protected-mode TSRs can be installed in the same way as
    real-mode TSRs, or they can be installed using D32TsrExit.  Either way,
    the TSR will remain in extended memory.  Use D32SegMoveLow to move code
    which will execute in real mode down to low memory during installation.
    If you install the TSR via the standard DOS or library functions, the
    parameter which indicates how much of the TSR to preserve on exit will
    be ignored.  The Tenberry kernel will automatically determines how much
    memory space your TSR requires.

    Activation: The TSR can be signaled (activated) by means of a software
    interrupt.  If a protected-mode TSR is signaled through a software
    interrupt, this raises the usual issues of protected-mode interrupt
    handling plus one additional major complication: another protected-mode
    program will not share either the protected-mode Interrupt Vector Table
    (IDT) or the protected-mode descriptor table (GDT or LDT) with the TSR.
    This means that both protected-mode and real-mode programs will only be
    able to signal the TSR through a real-mode interrupt, and will only be
    able to pass data in low memory (or by using absolute physical
    addresses).
    
    I/O Conflicts: Use D32TsrSavePSP during installation to save the I/O
    environment needed by the TSR.  Then use D32TsrSwitchPSP during TSR
    execution to switch from the initial I/O environment to the TSR's I/O
    environment on entry and back to the initial I/O environment on exit.

    Removal: Removing a TSR from memory (uninstalling it) will cause
    serious problems unless the interrupt handler chain and/or keyboard
    handler is restored to its original state (so that you don't try to
    signal the TSR after it has been removed from memory).  This is more
    difficult in protected mode, and not possible in some protected-mode
    environments.  Everything which has been installed has to be removed
    before the TSR itself can be removed (all keyboard hooks, real-mode
    callbacks and interrupt vectors); interrupt vectors in particular have
    to be restored to their original state.  This can't happen if another
    interrupt handler has been chained to your interrupt handler after the
    TSR was installed, and it can't happen in certain DPMI environments
    where the host does not permit real-mode interrupt handlers to be
    removed.  At present there is no API function to check whether the TSR
    can be safely uninstalled.  Use D32DPMIRmSetVector to restore the
    original vectors for any real-mode interrupts hooked by your TSR.  If
    all these operations succeed, use D32TsrExit to actually remove (and
    exit from) the TSR.

    This example shows how to write and install a protected-mode Terminate-
    and-Stay-Resident program, and how to signal that TSR by means of a
    software interrupt from either real mode or protected mode.

    The example consists of the following files in the EXAMPLES\TSRDEMO
    directory:

    TSRDEMO.C      The main TSR program.
    
    TSFEXECA.ASM   The assembly source for the execution context switcher.
    
    TSRDEMOA.ASM   The assembly source for the TSR real-mode interrupt
                   handler.
    
    SIGRM.C        The source for the real-mode signal program.
    
    SIGRMA.ASM     The assembly source for the real-mode catcher when the
                   TSR exits.
                   
    SIGPM.C        The source for the protected-mode signal program.

    MAKEFILE       Polymake-configured makefile to build all the example
                   executables using Microsoft VC 4.x and/or Watcom.
